---

<Base
  title="Top 10 MCP Servers for Data Science and Analytics in 2026 — AgentRank"
  description="The 10 highest-scoring MCP servers for data science: DuckDB, Jupyter, Spark, ClickHouse, dbt, GA4, Airflow, Snowflake, E2B, BigQuery. Scored by real signals — stars, freshness, issue health, contributors. Updated March 2026."
  activeTab="blog"
  keywords="best MCP servers data science, mcp data analytics, ai agent data tools, jupyter MCP server, duckdb MCP data science, dbt MCP server, clickhouse MCP analytics, airflow MCP server, bigquery MCP, apache spark MCP, snowflake MCP 2026"
  canonicalUrl="https://agentrank-ai.com/blog/best-mcp-servers-data-science/"
  jsonLd={[jsonLd, faqJsonLd]}
  ogImage="/og/best-mcp-servers-data-science.png"
>
  <article class="blog-post">
    <header class="post-header">
      <div class="breadcrumb"><a href="/blog/">Blog</a> <span>/</span></div>
      <h1>Top 10 MCP Servers for Data Science and Analytics in 2026</h1>
      <div class="post-meta">
        <time datetime={publishDate}>March 19, 2026</time>
        <span class="sep">&middot;</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
        <span class="sep">&middot;</span>
        <span>AgentRank Index</span>
      </div>
      <p class="lede">
        Data science workflows are a natural fit for MCP. An agent that can run a Jupyter cell,
        query DuckDB, trigger a dbt model, stream from ClickHouse, fire an Airflow DAG, and read
        Spark job history can replace hours of manual pipeline inspection. We scored
        <strong>{stats.totalDataScienceTools} data science tools</strong> in the AgentRank index.
        These are the ten worth depending on.
      </p>
    </header>

    <nav class="toc">
      <strong>Contents</strong>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="#rankings">Rankings by score</a></li>
        <li><a href="#by-workflow">Choosing by workflow</a></li>
        <li><a href="#by-use-case">Detailed breakdown</a></li>
        <li><a href="#what-to-watch">What to watch for</a></li>
        <li><a href="#methodology">Methodology</a></li>
        <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <section id="rankings">
      <h2>Top 10 data science MCP servers</h2>
      <p>
        Ranked by the composite AgentRank score — a weighted blend of stars (15%), freshness (25%),
        issue health (25%), contributors (10%), and inbound dependents (25%).
        Average score across all {stats.totalDataScienceTools} data science tools is <strong>{stats.avgDataScienceScore}</strong>.
        Only 2.3% of the 25,000+ tool index scores above 60 — every tool in this list clears that bar.
      </p>

      <table class="data-table top-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="num">#</th>
            <th>Repository</th>
            <th class="num">Score</th>
            <th class="num">Stars</th>
            <th>Use Case</th>
            <th>Lang</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {tools.map((tool) => (
            <tr>
              <td class="num rank-num">{tool.rank}</td>
              <td class="tool-cell">
                <a href={`/tool/${tool.slug}/`} class="tool-link">{tool.name}</a>
                <span class="tool-desc">{tool.desc}</span>
              </td>
              <td class="num score-cell">{tool.score}</td>
              <td class="num">{tool.stars.toLocaleString('en-US')}</td>
              <td class="use-case">{tool.useCase}</td>
              <td class="lang-badge">{tool.lang}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section id="by-workflow">
      <h2>Choosing by workflow</h2>
      <p>
        The ten tools cover distinct workflow stages. Pick based on where you spend time,
        not by score alone.
      </p>

      <table class="data-table workflow-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Workflow need</th>
            <th>Best pick</th>
            <th class="num">Score</th>
            <th>Why</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
